  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is considered a **felony** in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained money (from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, or other crimes) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. \n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is prosecuted under federal law, primarily through the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Substantial fines** (up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater).\n- **Imprisonment** (up to 20 years per offense, depending on the specifics of the crime).\n- **Asset forfeiture** (seizure of property or funds involved in the laundering).\n\nAdditionally, money laundering is often prosecuted alongside other crimes, such as fraud, tax evasion, or racketeering, which can lead to even harsher penalties. \n\nIt's important to note that the exact laws and penalties may vary by jurisdiction, but money laundering is universally treated as a serious crime. If you\u2019re facing such allegations, consulting an experienced criminal defense attorney is highly recommended.",
